# React TypeScript Patterns

Best practices and patterns for React components using TypeScript.

<rule>
name: react_typescript_patterns
description: Standards for React component development with TypeScript

sections:
  - name: api_type_derivation
    description: |
      Derive exact types from API type definitions for component props and state:

      ```typescript
      import type { Endpoints } from "@octokit/types"
      
      // Define prop types using exact API response types
      type GithubOrg = Endpoints["GET /user/orgs"]["response"]["data"][0]
      type GithubRepo = Endpoints["GET /orgs/{org}/repos"]["response"]["data"][0]

      interface ProjectDialogProps {
        onClose: () => void
        org?: GithubOrg
        repo?: GithubRepo
      }
      ```

      Benefits:
      1. Ensures component props match API response structure exactly
      2. Automatic type updates when API types change
      3. Better type safety than manual interface definitions
      4. IDE autocompletion for all API response fields

  - name: data_loading_hooks
    description: |
      Use tuple returns for data loading hooks in React components:

      ```typescript
      // Hook definition
      function useAuthenticatedFetch<T>(url: string | undefined): [T | null, boolean, Error | null] {
        // Implementation...
      }

      // Usage in component
      function OrgList(): JSX.Element {
        const [orgs, isLoading, _error] = useAuthenticatedFetch<GithubOrg[]>(API_ORGS_URL)

        if (isLoading) {
          return <CircularProgress />
        }

        return (
          <List>
            {orgs?.map((org) => (
              <ListItem key={org.id}>{org.login}</ListItem>
            ))}
          </List>
        )
      }
      ```

      Benefits:
      1. Consistent pattern for handling async data states
      2. Type-safe loading and error states
      3. Clean component rendering logic
      4. Easy to handle undefined/loading states

examples:
  - description: "Component with API types and loading states"
    input: |
      function ProjectList() {
        const data = await fetchProjects()
        return <div>{data.map(p => p.name)}</div>
      }
    output: |
      type Project = Endpoints["GET /projects"]["response"]["data"][0]

      function ProjectList(): JSX.Element {
        const [projects, isLoading, _error] = useAuthenticatedFetch<Project[]>('/api/projects')

        if (isLoading) {
          return <CircularProgress />
        }

        return (
          <List>
            {projects?.map((project) => (
              <ListItem key={project.id}>{project.name}</ListItem>
            ))}
          </List>
        )
      }

